# {{PROJECT_NAME}} — Operating Contract

> The single governing law for the {{PROJECT_NAME}} system. Every repo in the
> system carries a thin pointer (`CLAUDE.md` / `AGENTS.md` /
> `.github/copilot-instructions.md`) back to this contract. If a rule is not
> here or in the brain, it does not bind.

## §0 The one rule

**One system, many repos.** Treat the project as a single workspace. State lives
in exactly two planes:

- **GitHub** — execution and coordination (issues, project board, branches, PRs, Actions).
- **This brain** (`{{BRAIN_REPO}}`) — memory and governance (this contract,
  decisions, policies, continuity logs, the generated capabilities map).

If a fact is not in one of those two planes, it does not exist. There is no
external source of truth (no chat-only context, no private drive). **Pushing to
GitHub is the durable sync.**

## §1 Member repos

The brain coordinates the app repos listed in `brain.manifest.json` under
`app_repos`. The brain itself (`{{BRAIN_REPO}}`) is the governance/memory repo.

## §2 Branch model (GitHub Flow)

- One long-lived branch: `main`, always releasable, branch-protected (PR + CI required).
- One branch per issue: `feat/<issue>-slug`, `fix/<issue>-slug`, `chore/<slug>`.
- Squash-merge and auto-delete the branch: one issue, one clean commit.
- Sync discipline: `git fetch --prune` and check active branches/issues **before**
  claiming work; **push after every commit**.

## §3 Multi-agent coordination (claim, check, warn)

The lock is the issue plus the branch — visibility, not hard locks.

1. `git fetch --prune`; read the issue. If assigned or it has an open branch/PR,
   stop and pick another (overlap warning).
2. Self-assign the issue; set status in progress.
3. Create and push the branch early (a visible claim).
4. Record the claim in the active-agents registry; clear it on merge.

Two local agents on one machine use git worktrees. Local and cloud agents are
physically isolated; cloud agents land work via PR + CI, never directly on `main`.

## §4 The session ritual (automatic, never reminded)

Every core command and the session hooks bake this in.

**Open:** read this contract + the latest `05-logs/` entry + the master index;
`git fetch --prune`; check for overlap; set the model + effort to fit the work;
state the objective; claim the issue.

**Close:** append a continuity entry to `05-logs/<date>-<topic>.md` (what changed,
why, evidence); update the decision board if any decision changed; run the
anti-drift sweep (regenerate the capabilities map, validate the docs mesh);
update the board/issue/PR state; push everything (the durable sync).

A SessionEnd hook runs the mechanical half of close automatically as a safety net:
it pushes already-committed work and writes a continuity checkpoint. It never
stages app code or live config.

## §5 The self-extending brain

- **Derived layer (from code):** the capabilities map (`01-docs/CAPABILITIES.md`)
  is generated by scanning the app repos and the brain's commands. Truth comes
  from code, so it cannot drift.
- **Intent layer (from the session):** any session that adds a capability
  registers it (one line: what, why, where). CI gates enforce this — a feature
  cannot land without the brain growing with it.

## §6 Model and effort

Set the AI model and reasoning effort to fit the activity **before** executing.
Each core command declares its default tier (see the command catalog). Switch if
the task does not match.

## §7 Framework relationship

This brain was instantiated from the `brain-factory` hub and records
its `framework_version` in `brain.manifest.json`. Core modules are hub-owned and
upgraded via `{{CMD_PREFIX}}-upgrade`; project extensions are owned here and never overwritten
by the hub. Proven improvements are sent upstream via `{{CMD_PREFIX}}-learn`.

## §8 Security and secrets

Secrets never enter the brain or any public repo. Live config is never staged by
automation. Security-sensitive intake follows the brain's security policy in
`04-policies/`.
